'''Yatsurugi Shrine''' (やつるぎじんじゃ) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Suwa, Nagano|ja|諏訪市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Nagano Prefecture. Formerly classified as a {{ill|Prefectural Shrine|ja|県社|12=draft|12=draft}}, it enshrines three deities: {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主|12=draft|12=draft}} as Yachihoko no Kami, {{ill|Yamato Takeru|ja|ヤマトタケル|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Emperor Ōjin|ja|応神天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}. It serves as a sub-shrine of the {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|12=draft|12=draft}} Upper Shrine.

== History ==
Originally located on Takashima in {{ill|Lake Suwa|ja|諏訪湖|12=draft|12=draft}}, the shrine was historically built using funds raised through shipbuilding taxes on Lake Suwa. During the construction of {{ill|Takashima Castle|ja|高島城|12=draft|12=draft}} by {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|12=draft|12=draft}}, the shrine was relocated to its present location. During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, the {{ill|Suwa clan|ja|諏訪氏|1=Suwa clan|12=draft|12=draft}}, lords of Takashima Domain, venerated the shrine as a guardian of their castle. Since the {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治|12=draft|12=draft}}, it has been worshiped as the tutelary deity of Kowada Village.

== Suwa Lake Crossing Ritual ==
The shrine is notable for its unique ritual, the '''Lake-Crossing Ritual''' (みわたりしんじ). Commonly referred to as the "Observation of the Lake-Crossing Ritual," it is performed by the shrine's {{ill|Kannushi|ja|神職|12=draft|12=draft}} (Shinto priests). (See also {{ill|Lake Suwa#Omiwatari|ja|諏訪湖#御神渡り|御神渡り|12=draft|12=draft}}).

When the "Omiwatari" phenomenon is observed on Lake Suwa, the shrine convenes an extraordinary council to determine the date for the observation ceremony. Prior to the ceremony, the chief priest and other shrine officials place sacred ropes ({{ill|Shimenawa|ja|注連縄|12=draft|12=draft}}) on their household gates and undertake a period of ritual purification ({{ill|Shōjin kessai|ja|精進潔斎|12=draft|12=draft}}). On the day of the ceremony, they perform a purification rite (修祓) at the shrine before heading to Lake Suwa.

At the lake, the priests inspect the ice formations, including the primary (一之御渡), secondary (二之御渡), and Saku no Miwatari (佐久之御渡) crossings, as well as both lower and upper shorelines. Upon returning to the shrine, a "Report Ritual" (奉告祭) is conducted to inform the enshrined deities of the lake's conditions. Based on these observations, predictions about the year’s harvest, societal fortune, and climate are made. The results are compiled into a "Report Document" (注進状) and submitted during the "Lake-Crossing Report Ceremony" (御渡注進式) at the {{ill|Suwa-taisha|lt=Suwa Taisha Upper Shrine|ja|諏訪大社#上社|12=draft|12=draft}}. The shrine then forwards the information to the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|12=draft|12=draft}} and the [[:en:Japan_Meteorological_Agency|Japan Meteorological Agency]].<ref>During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, these reports were submitted to the {{ill|Tokugawa shogunate|ja|Tokugawa shogunate|12=draft|12=draft}}.</ref>

The most recent instance of this ritual occurred in [[2013]], with the observation on January 22, the ceremony on January 25, and the report submission on February 17. In years when the "Omiwatari" is not observed, the ritual still takes place, with a report stating "No crossing was observed." In such cases, Lake Suwa is referred to as "the opening sea" (明けの海).

